<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST : LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
 PLANE ON WAY TO L.A. LOSES WING PANEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A panel broke off the left wing of a Los Angeles-bound Boeing 757 after 
takeoff, forcing the Eastern Airlines flight to return to Hartsfield Atlanta 
International Airport in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
None of the 105 passengers or crew of six was injured, said Robin Matell, an 
Eastern spokesman in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
The plane left Atlanta at 8:04 p.m. Thursday and was near Birmingham, Ala., 
when the pilot noticed the problem, said Jack Barker, a Federal Aviation 
Administration spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
"It was climbing at 28,000 feet and the captain felt a shudder and heard a 
noise," Matell said. 
</P>
<P>
The plane returned to the Atlanta airport an hour later, Matell said, and the 
passengers were transferred to another flight. 
</P>
<P>
"Eastern is investigating the incident to try to determine what caused it," 
Matell said. "We'll keep the plane out of service until we find out exactly 
what happened." 
</P>
</TEXT>
