<HEADLINE>
<P>
A RELEVANT FACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Regarding Lawrence Christon's bashing of comedian Jerry Seinfeld ("Laughing on 
Empty," Jan. 17): 
</P>
<P>
It is clear that Christon appreciates social relevance. And certainly nothing 
is wrong in that. 
</P>
<P>
The problem is that he demands it, as if perpetually posed on the edge of his 
seat for some piquant moment when the heavens open to reveal Deeper Truth. The 
merely hilarious, then, being short of that moment, apparently causes Larry to 
take his toys and go home. 
</P>
<P>
While comedy certainly benefits from the likes of the Lenny Bruces and the Mort 
Sahls, to be so myopic as to demand such of everyone discounts the 
contributions of the Three Stooges, "I Love Lucy," David Letterman -- and Jerry 
Seinfeld. 
</P>
<P>
STEVE TATHAM 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
