<HEADLINE>
<P>
REVOLUTIONARY BOAT FROM SAN PEDRO CHALLENGES FOR LITTLE AMERICA'S CUP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Special to The Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MELBOURNE, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A revolutionary sailboat from the Cabrillo Beach Yacht Club in San Pedro will 
start a best-of-7 series against the Australian defender of the Little 
America's Cup here Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
The competition -- known formally as the International Catamaran Challenge 
Trophy -- is for Class C catamarans 25 feet long. 
</P>
<P>
Class C catamarans are distinct for their airfoil wing-type sails, which 
inspired the design of the 60-foot Stars &amp; Stripes catamaran Dennis Conner 
sailed in a lopsided, 2-race defense of the America's Cup against New Zealand's 
130-foot monohull last September. 
</P>
<P>
The San Pedro boat, dubbed Wingmill, features an airfoil that rotates top to 
bottom like a pinwheel when the boat tacks or jibes (alters course across the 
wind direction). It will be sailed by brothers Steve and Brian Dair of San 
Pedro. 
</P>
<P>
The defender will be Edge II, a conventional Class C cat to be sailed by Simon 
McKeon and Dave Churcher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
CATAMARANS; LITTLE AMERICA'S CUP (YACHT RACE); YACHT RACING 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012189-0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 8313 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 21, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part 3; Page 4; Column 3; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
86 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At Wengen, Switzerland, Marc Girardelli, bidding for a third World Cup overall 
title, broke an 8-year record on the circuit's longest downhill course and 
widened his lead over defending champion Pirmin Zurbriggen. 
</P>
<P>
Girardelli skied the 4,185-meter run in 2 minutes 26.54 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
The Austrian-born skier completed a 7-day sweep of the two most difficult races 
on the circuit. He won last week on the equally hazardous Hahnenkamm course at 
Kitzbuehel, Austria, the first downhill victory of his 10-year career. 
</P>
