<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASKETBALL; 
</P>
<P>
EMPIRE LEAGUE ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
DESPITE INJURIES, EL DORADO GETS PAST CYPRESS, 56-45 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS KAISER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
El Dorado High School, playing without two important reserve players and with 
two starters hampered by injury, defeated Cypress, 56-45, in an Empire League 
boys' basketball game Friday at El Dorado. 
</P>
<P>
It was the lowest point total for the Hawks this season (they average 74 
points). But it was enough to keep El Dorado undefeated in league play and a 
game ahead of Cypress. El Dorado is 15-4 overall, 5-0 in the league. Cypress is 
9-10, 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
Cypress came back from a 17-point first-half deficit to get to within three 
with 1:56 remaining in the game. But the rally fell short. 
</P>
<P>
Despite losing reserves Shaun Facione (right knee) and Tim Murray (sprained 
ankle and fractured left wrist) this week for an indefinite period, and with 
starters Matt Luke and Mike Renaud hampered with minor injuries, the Hawks took 
control early. 
</P>
<P>
They had surged to a 6-0 lead on baskets by Luke, Renaud and Jerome Facione 
before Cypress scored with 4:35 remaining in the first period. 
</P>
<P>
"We're used to playing 9-10 guys a game," El Dorado Coach Wayne Carlson said. 
Losing coach Shaun Facione and Murray "takes away a little bit of our options." 
</P>
<P>
But Jerome Facione powered the El Dorado offense in the first quarter with 8 of 
the team's 16 points. He finished with 12. 
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, the Hawks built a 17-point lead, largely behind Luke. He 
scored 6 of his 14 points in the quarter. He also finished with 17 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
"In the first half, Luke killed us on the boards," said Cypress Coach Kevin 
Loftus. "And they did exactly what they wanted. 
</P>
<P>
"In the second half we geared up our defense and took away their break." 
</P>
<P>
Cypress closed a 15-point halftime gap to trail by only by nine going into the 
final period. But El Dorado got a free throw by Facione with 1:47 remaining and 
two baskets from Luke with under a minute to go for the 11-point victory. 
</P>
<P>
Los Alamitos 73, Katella 54 -- Los Alamitos outscored Katella, 27-10, in the 
third quarter, with forward Geoff Graham scoring 9 of his 11 points in the 
quarter. The big quarter came after Katella (6-11, 2-3) had cut Los Alamitos' 
10-point first-quarter lead to 4 (27-23) by halftime. Mike Wilson scored 14, 
Graham and Brent Overbeek each had 11 for Los Alamitos (8-12, 3-2). Brian 
Yourstone led Katella with 19. 
</P>
<P>
Loara 59, Esperanza 51 -- Tes Whitlock scored 21 points and had 7 assists to 
lead host Loara (3-13, 1-4). Joe Gaudio added 14 points and 8 rebounds, and 
Brad Leonard had 10 points and 7 rebounds for Loara, which took control by 
outscoring Esperanza, 14-5, in the second quarter to lead, 30-20, at the half. 
Esperanza is 6-13, 0-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012189-0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 8382 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 21, 1989, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part 3; Page 16; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
251 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASKETBALL; 
</P>
<P>
ANGELUS LEAGUE; 
</P>
<P>
MATER DEI FINISHES OFF SERVITE; 
</P>
<P>
RIGDON LEADS THIRD-QUARTER RUN FOR 79-56 VICTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LARRY NISTA, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Servite High School started something it couldn't finish against Mater Dei 
Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
The Friars kept close to Mater Dei, the second-ranked team in Orange County, 
through the first quarter and into the second. 
</P>
<P>
But Mater Dei took control late in the first half, and then Dylan Rigdon scored 
17 third-quarter points to lead the Monarchs past Servite, 79-56, in front of 
1,500 at UC Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
Mater Dei (20-2, 4-0) remained in first place in the Angelus League. Servite 
dropped to 11-7, 2-2. 
</P>
<P>
"We didn't have any letdowns," Mater Dei Coach Gary McKnight said. "We 
struggled a bit early but then we got things going." 
</P>
<P>
Rigdon, a 6-foot 4-inch senior guard, had 31 points to lead all scorers. 
</P>
<P>
Mike Morris, who had 15 points, opened the game for Mater Dei with a 3-pointer. 
</P>
<P>
Chris Johnson, who led the Friars with 15 points, answered with a 15-footer, 
prompting the Servite fans to litter the court with streams of toilet paper. 
</P>
<P>
A technical foul was called on Servite. Rigdon made both shots and Mater Dei 
was on its way to an early lead. 
</P>
<P>
Servite rallied to get within 2 points twice, late in the first quarter and 
early in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
But Mater Dei took control of the boards in the second quarter and went on a 
late run, including a free throw by Rigdon and stolen pass and basket by Dan 
O'Neil at the buzzer, for a 37-22 halftime lead. 
</P>
<P>
Rigdon then started his assault with about 6 minutes left, hitting a 10-foot 
jump shot. He ended the quarter scoring 5 points within the closing seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Servite's Chris Johnson drives past Mater Dei's Dan O'Neil during game 
at the Bren Center. CHRISTINE WALTER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
