<P>
WESTMINSTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Suspected Molester Closely Guarded in Court 
</P>
<P>
Suspected child molester James A. Hydrick appeared for arraignment in West 
Orange County Municipal Court on Friday with five deputy marshals closely 
guarding him. 
</P>
<P>
Hydrick, an expert in karate who faces 13 counts of child molestation, was 
denied a restraining order for what his attorney called "verbal abuse by 
deputies" in jail. 
</P>
<P>
Municipal Judge Michael Beecher also postponed Hydrick's arraignment until Feb. 
6 at the request of public defender Pamela Boyd. The request was "a defense 
tactic," Boyd said later. 
</P>
<P>
Boyd said she sought the restraining order because sheriff's deputies at County 
Jail verbally abused Hydrick. Beecher told her that specific complaints should 
be directed to jail officials. 
</P>
<P>
Hydrick, 29, sat in a booth enclosed by a metal screen as two deputy marshals 
stood behind him. Three other marshals stood by the front entrance to the 
courtroom. The extra security precautions were taken because Hydrick is 
considered an escape risk, Lt. Les Weaver of the marshal's office said. Hydrick 
reportedly has escaped from at least three jails. 
</P>
<P>
Hydrick was returned to Orange County earlier this month from a Georgia jail to 
face the molestation charges. Deputy Dist. Atty. Michael Koski said the charges 
involve a small group of Huntington Beach boys that Hydrick allegedly 
befriended while living there last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
